{[%evp 0,37,19,24,25,1,1,-14,0,0,23,4,4,4,1,12,17,17,40,34,21,21,13,10,37,17,-1,8,3,4,19,18,15,32,27,31,31,28,33,33]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 {As usual in the Catalan parts, we prefer to cover the bishop check with its counterpart.} ({A different theoretical line is starting with} 4. Nd2 c5 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 cxd4) 4... Bxd2+ ({In case of} 4... c5 5. Bxb4 cxb4 6. Bg2 O-O {Black has still to solve the task of mobilizing the queenside and Bc8 in particular after the flexible} 7. e3) (4... Qe7 {is also on the verge of the relevant branch in the Bogo-Indian.} 5. Bg2 {is still making a difference to it exactly because White has Bg2 on the board before committing his Ng1.} Nc6 (5... O-O 6. Nf3 {will most probably transpose to the deviation from the leading text with 5...0-0 6. Bg2 d6 7.Nf3 Qe7, see below}) 6. e3 $5 {[%cal Gg1e2] This move in the spirit of the English Opening (the knight is going to appear on e2) is both the way to bring originality to the position and to fight for an opening advantage. Indeed, 6.Nc3, a major alternative in the Bog-Indian line, is not an option because of the hanging d4-pawn.} (6. Nf3 {leads to the main variation of the Bogo-Indian with 4...Qe7 -} Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 (7. Qxd2 {is inaccurate because of} Ne4 {[%cal Ge7b4]}) 7... d6 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) 6... e5 (6... O-O 7. Ne2 Bxd2+ (7... d5 $6 {is imprecise on the account of} 8. a3 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 $1 Rd8 10. Rc1 {and now:} e5 (10... dxc4 {is just opening the big diagonal in front of the Catalan bishop, after} 11. Nxc4 {the harsh attempt at solving the opening problems by} e5 $6 {does not pass the test after the principled} 12. Bxc6 $1 (12. O-O exd4 13. exd4 Bg4 14. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 12... exd4 13. Bf3 dxe3 14. Qb3 {and there is little in return for the piece, e.g.} Bg4 15. Bxg4 exf2+ 16. Kf1 $1 Nxg4 17. Qf3 h5 18. h3 Nf6 19. Kg2 $16) 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. e4 Nb6 13. d5 Nb8 14. O-O c6 15. Nc3 $16) 8. Qxd2 ({from the last note we already know that in reply to} 8. Nxd2 {Black should better revert to the plan with} e5 9. O-O d6) 8... d5 ({here, on the contrary, Black is well-advised to prefer the text move to} 8... d6 $6 9. Nbc3 e5 10. h3 {[%cal Ge1g1]} Bf5 11. O-O $16 {[%cal Ga1e1]}) 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nbc3 $14) 7. d5 $14 Bxd2+ (7... Nb8 $143 8. Nc3 a5 9. Nge2 d6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 $16) 8. Nxd2 ({solid and good enough is} 8. Qxd2 Nb8 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nge2 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ge1g1]}) 8... Nb8 (8... Nb4 9. a3 Nd3+ 10. Ke2 Nc5 ({Black will have anyway to retreat after the funny interpolation} 10... Ng4 11. Nh3 $1) 11. b4 Na6 12. Ngf3 d6 13. e4 O-O 14. Re1 $14) 9. Ne2 d6 10. Nc3 a5 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Na6 13. Qb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) (4... a5 5. Bg2 d6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} (5... O-O 6. Nf3 (6. e4 $5 d6 $140 7. Ne2 e5 8. O-O {deserves attention}) 6... d5 {transposes to the 2nd part of the Catalan, Chapter 3. Black's last two moves can be played in the reversed order}) (5... Nc6 6. Nf3 d6 {transposes to the main continuation 5...d6, see below}) 6. Nf3 Nbd7 (6... Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. Be3 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3]} (8. Bg5 {has the similar idea of leaving Bb4 in dire straights -} exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. a3 Bc5 14. Nc3 c6 {has been played in Giri - Ivanchuk, Reggio Emilia, 2012, perhaps} 15. Na4 Be6 16. Rfc1 $14 {is the best way to point at the drawbacks of Black's structure. The text move is even more ambitious, for it takes the c5-square under control as well}) 8... exd4 (8... Ng4 $2 9. a3 {will cost Black one pawn at least}) 9. Nxd4 Ne5 (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 O-O 11. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 10. b3 a4 ({yet another problem with Bb4 arises after} 10... O-O 11. Nc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2b4]}) 11. a3 axb3 12. Nxb3 Ba5 13. c5 Nc4 14. Bd4 O-O 15. Qc2 d5 16. Nxa5 Rxa5 17. Nc3 c6 18. a4 $16 {[%csl Gd4]}) 7. O-O e5 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Nc3 Re8 10. e4 exd4 (10... Nb6 11. b3 Bg4 12. d5 $14) 11. Nxd4 Ne5 (11... Bc5 12. Nf5 Ne5 13. b3 $14 {may transpose after c7-c6}) ({the immediate} 11... c6 {weakens the d6-pawn and White has every reason to concentrate on it -} 12. Rad1 Ne5 13. Nce2 $1 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gf2f4]}) 12. b3 c6 13. h3 Bc5 14. Nf5 (14. Be3 $2 Bxh3 $1) 14... Bxf5 15. exf5 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1]} d5 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Bg5 d4 18. Nd5 Be7 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Rac1 $36 {[%csl Gd5,Gg2]}) (4... Be7 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 {also transposes to the 2nd part of the Catalan, see the Chapters from 4 to 11.}) 5. Qxd2 ({White does not need to play} 5. Nxd2 {without a particular reason -} Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd7d6]}) 5... d5 {This idea has recently gained in popularity.} ({Black's alternative set-up is} 5... O-O 6. Bg2 d6 {, which has already been discussed in the annotations to 4...Qe7, including the remark about the advantages for White when he is able to take on d2 with the queen so that Nb1 will reach its most natural square.} 7. Nf3 {and now:} Nc6 (7... Nbd7 8. Nc3 e5 9. O-O Re8 10. e4 $16 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ga1d1]}) (7... Qe7 8. Nc3 e5 9. O-O Re8 10. h3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} (10. e4 Bg4) 10... Nc6 (10... e4 $6 11. Ng5 {[%csl Re4]}) 11. e4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Qe5 14. Qe3 Be6 15. b3 $16 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf2f4]}) 8. Nc3 e5 9. O-O Bg4 (9... Re8 10. Rfd1 $14) 10. dxe5 $5 (10. d5 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nb8 $14) 10... dxe5 11. Qe3 $36 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga1d1,Gc3d5]}) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 c6 (7... Nbd7 8. O-O c6 {does not differ from the leading text}) (7... b6 8. cxd5 {yields White a lasting edge -} exd5 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. O-O $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf1d1,Gb2b4] , see the subline with 12...exd5 in the next note for more details}) 8. O-O dxc4 $5 {A change of the course, otherwise White will enjoy spatial advantage:} (8... b6 {is once again a bit passive -} 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Rac1 Qe7 (11... Nxe5 $6 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. f4 a6 15. Rfd1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 12. cxd5 {and now:} exd5 {reaches a pleasant version of the Carlsbad structure -} (12... cxd5 13. Nb5 $1 {and the threatened penetration should not be underestimated:} Ne8 (13... a6 {is nicely met by} 14. Rc7 $1 axb5 ({very picturesque is} 14... Rfb8 15. Qg5 $1 {[%cal Gc7d7]}) 15. Rxb7 Qd6 (15... Rxa2 16. Rc1 $36) 16. f4 Rfb8 (16... Rxa2 17. Rc1 $36 {[%cal Gc1c6]}) 17. Rxb8+ Qxb8 18. a3 $14 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gd2b4,Gf1c1]}) 14. Rc2 a6 15. Na3 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf1c1]}) 13. Nd3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gb2b4]} Ne4 (13... a5 14. e3 Rac8 15. Rc2 $14) 14. Qc2 Rfe8 15. e3 Ndf6 16. Rfe1 $14) (8... Nbd7 9. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Gb1d2]} (9. Rc1 {is a plausible alternative}) 9... b6 (9... Qe7 10. Nbd2 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 (12... cxd5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rd5] favors White, his prospects are higher after the text as well}) 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ga2a3,Ga1d1]}) 10. Nbd2 Bb7 (10... Ba6 11. b4 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4]}) 11. b4 $5 {A logical idea to expand on the queenside.} (11. e4 c5 $1 (11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 $14) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 Ne4 14. Rad1 cxd4 (14... Qe7 $143 {and White retains some pressure after} 15. Rfe1) 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Nxd4 Nxe5 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Qf6 19. Rfe1 Rae8 20. Kg2 g6 $11) 11... c5 (11... a5 12. a3 $14) (11... Qe7 12. c5 a5 13. a3 $14) 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. e4 Bb7 15. Rfb1 Rb8 16. e5 Nd5 17. dxc5 Qc7 18. Ne4 $14 Nxe5 $140 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 20. Qb2 Qc7 21. Nd6 Bc6 22. Qe5 $36) 9. Ne5 ({Alternatively, White can begin with} 9. a4 b5 10. axb5 ({in case of} 10. Ne5 Nd5 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Nc3 {Black has the important intermezzo} f6 $1 13. Ng4 $140 $1 Qd7 $1 {, when after} 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Ne3 Bb7 16. b3 {he has almost consolidated and has several options, such as 16...Rc8 and} a6 $13) 10... cxb5 11. Nh4 Nd5 12. Nc3 b4 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. e4 Be6 15. Qxb4 Nc6 16. Qc5 Rc8 17. exd5 Ne7 18. Qxa7 Nxd5 $44) 9... b5 10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Nc3 Nbd7 13. Rfd1 $1 ({Less pretending is} 13. Nxc6 {, as witnessed by} Qb6 14. d5 Nc5 15. Rfb1 b4 16. Na4 Nxa4 17. Rxa4 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxc6 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 $11 {and it is time to sign a draw.}) 13... Qc7 {The best - Bllack is immediately questioning the centralized knight.} (13... a6 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 (14... Qxd7 15. e4 Qc7 16. e5 Nd5 17. Ne4 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6]}) 15. Ne4 $1 Qe7 16. Qc3 Rfd8 17. b4 $14 {[%csl Rb7]}) (13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd5 (14... Qxd2 15. Rxd2 Nd5 16. Ne4 a5 17. Nc5 Ra7 18. f4 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge2e4]}) 15. Ne4 a5 (15... Qb6 $6 16. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rc5]}) 16. Nc5 {[%csl Gc5]} Qe7 17. Qd4 $44) 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. b4 Nf6 ({An evidence of White's total compensation is the curious line} 15... Rfd8 16. Qf4 $5 Qxf4 17. gxf4 a6 18. Ne4 Ra7 19. Nd2 Nb6 20. Nb3 Kf8 21. e3 Ke7 22. Na5 $14 {[%csl Rb7]}) 16. Ne4 $1 ({Compared to 13...a6 14.Nxd7 Qxd7, here Black is prepared to meet} 16. e4 {with} e5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. f4 Qc7 19. e5 Nd5 $11) 16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Rfd8 18. Qc3 h6 19. Rdc1 $44 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge2e3]} *

