{[%evp 0,43,19,25,27,3,4,-29,7,19,15,15,8,-25,-25,-10,-30,-29,-6,-11,-11,-5,9,-18,-23,-33,33,-35,29,65,57,56,45,37,32,32,39,66,93,77,81,82,91,85,81,62]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 b5 $6 ({The Snake-wise} 5... Bd6 $6 {is too time-consuming -} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. Nf3 Bc7 (8... Bf8 9. O-O d6 10. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ge2e4]}) 9. d6 $1 ({The point!} 9. O-O $1 d6 {would have justified Black's play}) 9... Ba5 10. O-O Bxc3 ({The d6-pawn is cutting Black's position into two parts and he has to put his hopes on initiating counterplay by using the e4-outpost; a humble move like} 10... Nc6 $6 {may invite} 11. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4f5] with emerging strong pressure on the kingside}) 11. bxc3 Ne4 12. Qd3 (12. Qd5 $5 Nxc3 13. Qxc5 Nxe2+ 14. Kh1) 12... Qf6 13. Nd2 $1 Nxc3 (13... Nxd6 14. Ba3 $16 {[%csl Rc5]}) (13... Nxd2 14. Bxd2 $16) 14. Re1 Nb5 15. Rb1 Nxd6 16. Ba3 Na6 17. e4 Qg6 18. f4 $16) 6. e4 $1 Nxe4 {Black is more or less obliged to take the challenge.} ({In case of} 6... Bb7 7. f3 {kills the bishop, thus leaving the whole queenside in trouble, for example} a6 8. a4 c4 9. Be3 Bb4+ 10. Kf2 O-O 11. Ne2 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 7. Bg2 $1 {It is important to follow the exact move order.} (7. Qe2 $143 Qe7 8. Bg2 Nd6 9. Be3 Na6 $13) 7... Nd6 {The alternatives are failing to impress:} (7... f5 $2 8. Bxe4 Qe7 (8... fxe4 $2 9. Qh5+ $18) 9. Ne2 fxe4 10. O-O Qf7 11. f3 e3 12. Nbc3 $18 {[%csl Re8]}) (7... Qe7 $2 8. Ne2 Nd6 9. O-O $18 {[%csl Re7,Re8][%cal Gf1e1]}) (7... Qa5+ 8. Nd2 $1 Nd6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Qd8 (11... Bf6 12. Ne5 $16) 12. a4 b4 13. Ne5 $16) 8. Bf4 $1 Be7 ({Black does not practically have any other choice, for instance} 8... Qe7+ $2 9. Ne2 {once again reveals the advantage of delaying the developing Ng1, e.g.} g5 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. h4 $18 {[%csl Re8]}) (8... Bb7 9. Nf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O {is just transposing.}) 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Bb7 (10... Na6 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Nc3 {does not differ from the main line either.}) 11. Re1 Na6 12. Nc3 Re8 (12... b4 $6 13. Bxd6 Bxd6 14. Ne4 Be7 (14... Qc7 $2 {is running into the familiar} 15. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gh4f5]}) 15. d6 {with domination after} Bf6 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Ne5 $1 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Rad8 19. Qd5 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Gd5,Gd6,Ge5]}) ({A major alternative is} 12... Nc7 {with new crossroads after} 13. Ne5 Rc8 {has been severely tested in online chess by} (13... Re8 $2 14. Ne4 $18) (13... Nde8 {is instructively met by} 14. d6 $1 Nxd6 15. Ng4 $1 Bxg2 16. Rxe7 $1 Bf3 (16... Qxe7 17. Bxd6 Qe6 18. Kxg2 $16) 17. Nh6+ $1 gxh6 18. Qxd6 Ne6 19. Bxh6 Re8 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Re1 ({a small improvement over} 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. Qxd5 Rb8 {and Black has managed to survive in Korogodski - Garau, ICCF email, 2015, even though White stays on top after the same} 23. Re1 $16) 21... f6 22. Re3 Bc6 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. Qxd5 Rd8 25. Re4 $16) 14. a4 $1 {and now:} a6 (14... b4 15. Nb5 $1 Ncxb5 16. axb5 Bg5 ({it is once again not recommendable to free the blockading d6-square, for instance} 16... Nxb5 $2 {and the same strike} 17. d6 $1 Nxd6 18. Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Rxa7 $18) 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Rxa7 $16) 15. axb5 Ncxb5 (15... axb5 16. Ra7 $16) 16. Nxb5 axb5 17. Ra7 Bg5 (17... Qb6 $2 18. Nxd7 Qxa7 19. Rxe7 $18) 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Rxb7 $1 (19. Nxd7 Rfd8 20. h4 Qf5 21. Re7 Rxd7 22. g4 Qxf2+ 23. Kxf2 Rxe7 $14) 19... Nxb7 20. d6 $1 Nxd6 (20... Na5 21. h4 $1 Qd8 22. Bd5 {with numerous threats -} Nc4 23. Bxf7+ Rxf7 24. Nxf7 Qf6 (24... Kxf7 25. Qd5+ Kf8 26. Re4 $18) 25. Re7 h6 26. Qd5 Nb6 27. Qb7 Rf8 28. Qxb6 Qf5 (28... Rxf7 29. Rxf7 Kxf7 30. Qxc5 $18) 29. Qxb5 Rxf7 30. Qe2 $16 {and White converted 18 moves later in L. Gleyzer - K. Rodriguez, ICCF email, 2018}) 21. Qxd6 {looks quite one-sided -} Rce8 22. Qd5 ({or} 22. f4 {at once -} Qe7 23. Rd1 $16) 22... Qf5 23. f4 $16 {G. Terreaux - V. Zolochevsky, ICCF email, 2014.}) 13. Nd2 $1 {The critical continuation.} ({Here} 13. Ne5 Bg5 {has led to a lively skirmish after} 14. Nc6 dxc6 15. dxc6 Bxf4 16. cxb7 Rb8 17. gxf4 Nc7 {, after} 18. Rxe8+ Ncxe8 19. Qe2 b4 20. Nd5 Rxb7 {White has compensation, but hardly more -} 21. Re1 Kh8 $13 {F. Hoffmann - M. Van Tricht, ICCF email, 2013.}) 13... Bf8 (13... Nc7 {saves the b5-pawn, but then its neighbor becomes a target -} 14. Nb3 $1 b4 (14... c4 15. Nc5 Ba6 16. b4 $16) 15. Nxc5 $1 bxc3 16. Bxd6 Bxd6 17. Nxb7 Qf6 {So far V. Schubert - T. Schmitz, GER, email, 2013, after} 18. bxc3 $1 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 $16 {it is already Black, who has to prove compensation for the missing pawn.}) 14. Rxe8 Nxe8 ({The d6-square needs control, Black will inevitably part with the extra pawn, but} 14... Qxe8 $2 15. Bxd6 Bxd6 16. Nxb5 Bf8 17. Nc4 $16 {is both strategical and tactical failure.}) 15. Nxb5 Nb4 ({If Black is relying on this resource, then this is the moment for it rather than} 15... d6 16. Nc4 $16 {and the d3-square is no longer accessible for Na6.}) 16. Nc3 ({A sound alternative is the immediate} 16. Nc4 Ba6 17. a4 d6 $14 {, but the text move keeps an option of trading the light-squared bishops before planting the knight.}) 16... Nd3 (16... Ba6 {is very likely to transpose after} 17. Be3) 17. Be3 Ba6 18. Bf1 $1 $146 ({A clear improvement upon} 18. b3 g6 19. Bf1 {, which has taken place in O. Zelenyuk - O. Zakharov, ICCF email, 2018,} d6 $14) 18... Qc8 ({Here, in reply to} 18... g6 {White can spare time on the b-pawn by} 19. Qb1 $1 Nb4 20. Nc4 $16) ({After} 18... Qb6 {the advance} 19. b3 {is fully justified, as Qb6 is exposed to various jumps.}) 19. b3 {[%cal Gd2c4]} d6 (19... Nd6 20. Nde4 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 $16) 20. Nc4 ({Besides this natural move, it makes sense to deprive Nd3 of the central square -} 20. f4 $5 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd2c4]}) 20... Bxc4 21. bxc4 Ne5 22. h3 $16 {[%csl Ge3,Gf1]} *

