{[%evp 0,43,19,27,18,3,4,-11,19,8,2,2,33,28,71,60,34,25,22,10,46,54,43,28,20,20,0,7,11,12,27,7,11,11,11,14,12,19,19,-15,-21,-36,-6,0,4,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 (9... Bf5 $2 {may be justified only if Black can jump to the e4-square on the next move, but} 10. Nd2 {[%cal Ge2e4] , simultaneously starting the famous Nimzowitch pirouette, nips this intention into the bud. The next White's moves are both natural and hard to meet:} Qd7 (10... Na6 11. Nc4 ({indeed, White can start with seizing space -} 11. e4 Bg4 12. f3 Bd7 13. Nc4 Ne8 14. a4 $16 {Aronian - Vachier Lagrave, Paris, 2021}) 11... Nc7 ({the attempt at regaining control over the key central square by} 11... Re8 $6 {is just falling short to} 12. Nb5 {and the d6-pawn is doomed. However, the position remains tricky, as witnessed by the sample line} Bf8 13. Bf4 {[%csl Rd6]} Be4 14. Ncxd6 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Bxd6 16. Nxd6 Re7 17. e4 Nxe4 18. Nc4 Nb4 19. d6 Re6 20. Re1 b5 21. a3 bxc4 22. axb4 g5 23. Qd5 gxf4 24. Rxe4 Rxd6 25. Qxc5 fxg3 26. hxg3 Qd7 27. Rxc4 {and, despite White's material and positional advantage, there is still technical work to do}) 12. Bf4 Nfe8 13. a4 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 11. a4 (11. e4 Bh3 12. a4 {is once again a full opening success for White}) 11... Bh3 12. Nc4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qe7 14. Bf4 Ne8 15. Qd3 Nd7 16. e4 $16 Ne5 $2 17. Bxe5 $1 Bxe5 18. f4 Bxc3 (18... Bg7 19. e5 dxe5 20. d6 $18) 19. bxc3 $18) ({the other bishop's sally} 9... Bg4 $2 {is analogously met by} 10. Nd2 Na6 (10... Qd7 11. a4 Bh3 {- 9....Bf5}) (10... Re8 11. a4 $16) 11. Nc4 Qd7 12. a4 $16 {with Bc1-f4 to follow}) (9... Qe7 10. Bf4 (10. Re1 $5 Nbd7 11. e4) 10... Nbd7 {leads back to the leading text.}) ({9...b6 and} 9... Na6 10. Re1 Re8 ({as well as} 10... Nc7 11. a4 Re8 12. Nd2 {will all transpose to other Chapters and will be respectively examined in them.})) 10. Bf4 Qe7 11. a4 ({Another popular moves are:} 11. Re1) (11. h3) 11... Ng4 (11... a6 {transposes to the next Chapter}) (11... Re8 $2 12. Nb5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6][%cal Gb5c7]}) (11... h6 {[%cal Gg6g5]} 12. Qc1 g5 (12... Kh7 13. Nb5 {This is not just a one-move threat; the knight is en route to a perfect square.} Ne8 14. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} a6 15. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4,Ge2e4]} f5 (15... Rb8 16. Nc4 b5 17. Na5 $16) 16. Nc4 g5 17. Bd2 Nef6 18. Bc3 Ne4 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nfd2 $16 {[%csl Rg7]}) 13. Bd2 Ng4 14. h4 (14. h3 $5 Nge5 15. h4 {is also possible, but why should not White plat the latter in one go?}) 14... f6 {[%csl Rg7]} (14... gxh4 15. Nxh4 $16 {[%csl Rf5,Rg8,Rh6]}) 15. b4 $1 {A remarkable break!} cxb4 16. Nb5 a5 17. Qc7 f5 {So far Llanes Hurtado - Bacrot, Montpellier, 2015, when White's best bet seems to be} 18. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Gb5d6] , the d5-pawn will soon be his main asset.}) (11... b6 12. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} (12. Qd2 $5) 12... Ng4 (12... a6 13. h3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge2e4]} Rb8 14. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Ne8 15. Bg5 f6 16. Be3 $16 b5 $2 17. axb5 axb5 18. b4 $1 $18) 13. Bg5 (13. Qd2 $5) 13... Bf6 $6 (13... f6 14. Bd2) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. h3 Nge5 16. Nd2 Ba6 17. Nb5 Bxb5 18. axb5 $16 {Najer - Alekseenko, Moscow, 2017.}) 12. Bg5 $1 {A surprising idea - White would like to close the scope of Bg7 as soon as the latter has received a green light. We are still going to see a similar approach in the next Chapter.} (12. Re1 a6 {reaches the mentioned relevant position with the same} 13. Bg5 $5) (12. Qc1 $5) 12... f6 (12... Bf6 13. Bxf6 Ngxf6 14. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd1c2]}) 13. Bd2 Nde5 ({In reply to the other jump} 13... Nge5 14. Nb5 $1 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gb5c7] is causing certain trouble}) (13... f5 {looks natural, but it is also allowing a penetration on the weakened e6-square by} 14. Ng5 $1 (14. Re1 $5) 14... Ndf6 (14... Nde5 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. dxe6 Nf6 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 $16 {Harsha - Sunilduth Lyna, Bishkek, 2015}) 15. Qb3 Re8 16. e4 h6 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18. dxe6 Qxe6 19. Qxe6+ Rxe6 20. exf5 gxf5 {with huge compensation, Eelvelt - Postupa, ICCF email, 2018, one of the many promising lines is} 21. Rad1 $5 Ne4 22. Nb5 Rd8 23. Bf4 $16) 14. h3 Nxf3+ 15. exf3 $1 {An instructive moment - Black has managed to exchange the potentially dangerous knight, but from now on, the e-file will constantly remind him of the hole on e6.} Ne5 16. Re1 Qd8 17. Bf1 {[%cal Gf3f4]} ({A plausible alternative is} 17. f4 $5 {, for instance} Nc4 18. Bc1 $16) 17... g5 ({After} 17... f5 18. f4 Nd7 {White can fix the advantage with the help of the instructive knight maneuver to the perfect c4-location by} 19. Nb5 $1 Nf6 20. Bc3 $16 {[%cal Gb5a3,Ga3c4]}) 18. f4 (18. Ne4 $5) 18... Ng6 19. Ne2 ({Just like on the previous move,} 19. Ne4 $5 {deserves serious attention.}) 19... Bd7 20. Qc2 Qc8 21. Kh2 Bh6 22. Ra3 $16 {Goryachkina - Alekseev, Yaroslavl, 2018.} *

