{[%evp 0,47,19,20,20,5,-1,-26,8,2,2,6,28,28,45,40,43,22,10,14,74,35,43,33,49,32,42,8,19,31,71,22,27,24,37,79,55,36,40,37,5,15,16,-3,56,76,73,60,73,104]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O a6 10. a4 Nbd7 (10... Re8 11. Re1 {will be examined in the next Chapters, a worthy alternative is} (11. Bf4 $5)) 11. Bf4 $5 {[%csl Rd6]} ({Here too, White is trying to economize time on} 11. Re1 Rb8 {etc.}) 11... Qc7 (11... Ne8 12. Qd2 (12. e4 $5) 12... Rb8 13. Rfb1 $5 $146 {[%cal Gb2b4]} ({going for the b2-b4 break; if White does not want to be that artificial, then} 13. Rab1 {would be his natural choice}) 13... b6 (13... b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. b4 $16) (13... Nb6 14. Qd3 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge2e4]}) 14. b4 Qc7 15. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gc1c8]}) (11... Qe7 12. Re1 ({Only now, even though both} 12. h3 {and}) (12. e4 {are quite attractive}) 12... Rb8 (12... Ng4 13. Bg5 $5 (13. a5 $14) 13... f6 (13... Bf6 $6 14. Bxf6 Ngxf6 15. e4 $16) 14. Bd2 Rb8 15. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] and White will follow the abovementioned plan on the queenside}) ({in case of} 12... Nh5 13. Bg5 {is causing even more inconvenience}) (12... h6 13. Qc1 $1 (13. e4 Ng4 $13) 13... g5 (13... Kh7 14. h3) 14. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4]}) 13. h3 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge2e4]} (13. e4 Ng4 $13) 13... h6 (13... b5 $6 14. e4 $1 b4 (14... Ne8 15. axb5 axb5 16. Ra7 $36 b4 $2 17. e5 $1 bxc3 18. Bg5 $18) 15. e5 $1 bxc3 (15... dxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 $16) 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) (13... Nh5 14. Bg5 Nhf6 (14... Bf6 15. Bh6 Bg7 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4]} b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. b4 $1) (14... f6 15. Bd2 f5 16. e4 $16) 15. e4 h6 16. Bf4 {and, after several twists, the position has suddenly transposed to 13...h6 14.e4, see below}) 14. e4 g5 (14... Nh5 15. Be3) 15. Bxd6 $1 (15. Bd2 b5 $13) 15... Qxd6 16. e5 Qb6 (16... Nxe5 $6 17. Nxe5 $16 {[%cal Ge5c4]}) 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Qd2 $1 (18. Qc2 Ne8 $13 {took place in Bareev - Alekseev, Khanty-Mansiysk, 2007,} 19. a5 Qd8 {with mutual chances}) 18... Re8 (18... Ne8 $6 19. a5 Qd8 20. Na4 $1 $16 {reveals the point behind White's refinement on the move 18 - the a5-pawn is protected!}) 19. Ne5 Bf5 20. g4 Bd7 21. Re2 Rbd8 22. Rae1 $14) 12. e4 {Grabbing the chance to advance the central pawn without deep preparation.} ({White has many other decent alternatives like} 12. Rc1) (12. h3) ({and} 12. Re1) 12... Re8 {Black has already to reckon with the central blow:} (12... Rb8 $2 {just misses} 13. e5 $1 dxe5 (13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. d6 {will just transpose}) 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. d6 Qb6 16. Bxe5 Be6 17. Re1 $16 {[%csl Gd6]}) (12... Nh5 {is aimed at disabling it, but there are more opening problems to be solved after} 13. Bd2 (13. Be3 $5) 13... Rb8 14. Rc1 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4] , for example} b5 (14... Nhf6 15. h3 Re8 16. Re1 $16) 15. b4 $1 Re8 (15... c4 $6 {is equivalent to a strategical resignation on the queenside -} 16. axb5 axb5 17. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rb5,Rc6][%cal Gf3d4]}) (15... Qb7 16. Rb1 $16) (15... Nhf6 16. Bf4 $16) 16. Re1 $36) ({the other jump} 12... Ng4 {is usually connected with the sequence} 13. Nd2 $1 Nge5 {, but Black has yet to decide about this knight after} 14. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Nd3 $1 {is probably Black's best way to anticipate the central breakthrough:} (14... c4 $6 {is a typical thrust for many Benoni types, though Black must execute it with great care, for example} 15. f4 Nd3 16. e5 $1 {puts him in trouble:} Nxb2 (16... dxe5 17. d6 $1 Qd8 {and here comes yet another typical break -} (17... Qxd6 18. Nxc4 $18 {[%csl Rd3,Rd6]}) 18. f5 $1 gxf5 19. Nxc4 e4 20. Nd5 $18) 17. Qc2 Nd3 18. Rab1 $1 dxe5 {may take the same turn after} 19. d6 Qd8 (19... Qxd6 20. Nxc4 $18 {[%csl Rd3,Rd6]}) 20. f5 $1 gxf5 21. Nd5 $18 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gd5e7]}) (14... Rb8 $6 {is similarly countered with} 15. f4 Nd3 16. e5 $1 b5 (16... dxe5 $2 17. d6 Qd8 18. f5 $18) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qe2 $1 N7xe5 (18... c4 $2 19. Ra7 Qd8 20. e6 $18) 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. h3 $1 ({still advantageous, but much more complicated is} 20. Nxb5 Bg4 21. Nxc7 Bxe2 22. Rfe1 Bd3 $16) 20... Qe7 (20... c4 21. Ra7 Qd8 22. Nce4 $18) 21. Rfe1 Re8 22. Bf4 $18) (14... f5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2f4]} Nf6 17. Nf4 Nfg4 18. Ra3 $16 {[%csl Re6]}) 15. Qb3 $1 ({now} 15. f4 $5 f5 {causes a fierce clash in the center -} 16. Qe2 $1 (16. exf5 $2 {is running into the surprising} Nf6 $1 {with the amusing point} 17. fxg6 $6 Ng4 $17) 16... fxe4 17. Ncxe4 (17. Ndxe4 $143 c4 $132) 17... Nxb2 (17... c4 $2 18. Nxd6 $1) 18. Ng5 $36) (15. h3 $5) 15... Rb8 ({it is important that White has enough time to answer} 15... N7e5 {with the cool-blooded} 16. h3 c4 17. Qa3 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge3d4]}) 16. h3 Re8 17. Nc4 N3e5 (17... N7e5 18. Nb6 Nd7 19. a5 Nxb6 20. axb6 Qe7 21. Na4 $16) 18. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rb5] A typical anti-Benoni maneuver, the knight does not only help in stopping the b7-b5 push, but it is always ready to be back on the excellent c4-square as soon as the latter is free:} f5 (18... c4 19. Qa2 Nc5 20. Nxc4 Nxc4 21. Qxc4 Bd7 22. Rfd1 $1 {[%csl Rd3]} Rbc8 (22... b5 23. axb5 axb5 24. Qb4 $1 $16) 23. a5 $16) 19. exf5 (19. f4 Nf7 $13 {[%cal Ge8e3]}) 19... gxf5 20. Rfe1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ga3c4] , slowly preparing to chase Ne5 under the most favourable circumstances.}) 13. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] Once again, our preference is going for the Nimzowitsch pirouette.} ({A heavy theory goes on with} 13. Re1 Ng4 14. Nd2 Nge5 15. Bf1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3]} Rb8 {etc.}) 13... Nh5 (13... Ne5 {is dubious in the view of} 14. Bxe5 Rxe5 15. a5 Nd7 16. Nc4 Re8 17. Na4 $16 {[%csl Rb6]}) 14. Be3 Rb8 (14... Ne5 15. h3 Bd7 {is another way to prepare the flank thrust, but the locations of the knight are not stable at all, as proved by} 16. g4 Nf6 17. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} c4 $140 18. a5 {(killing the queenside counterplay)} Bb5 19. Bb6 Qc8 20. Bd4 Nd3 21. Qe3 $16) 15. h3 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Qe2 $1 Qb6 {It is hard to recommend anything else:} (17... b4 $6 18. Nb5 Qb6 19. Na7 $16) (17... c4 18. Ra7 Qd8 19. Nxb5 $5 Rxb5 20. Nxc4 {[%csl Rb5,Rd6][%cal Gc4d6]} Rb8 21. g4 Nhf6 22. Nxd6 Re7 23. Rc1 Ne8 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. Nxc8 Qxc8 26. Qb5 Bf8 (26... Nd6 27. Qb4 {[%csl Rd6]}) 27. Bf4 $16) 18. g4 Nhf6 19. g5 $1 {Going for a material gain.} Nh5 20. Bf3 Ne5 (20... b4 $6 21. Nd1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd2c4]}) 21. Bxh5 Bxh3 $5 ({It is not only about White's extra pawn after} 21... gxh5 22. Qxh5 {, the march of his f-pawn is in the air, as demonstrated by} b4 23. f4 $1 bxc3 (23... Nd3 24. Ne2 $18) 24. fxe5 $18 {[%csl Rf7]}) 22. Bf3 Bxf1 23. Rxf1 Qc7 24. Bg2 $16 {White has every chance to convert his small material plus.} *

