{[%evp 0,35,20,20,20,-1,-9,-23,2,14,10,10,28,34,40,38,33,14,14,12,27,23,23,17,46,30,40,54,55,55,62,57,50,5,58,36,49,23]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 Ne4 {Although this jump is attached to Black's rare continuations, it has appeared at the highest level. Here are some other minor alternatives in brief:} ({Now and then, the bishop sally} 10... Bg4 $2 {is pointless until the e-pawn is still on its initial square, White is considerably better by simple means -} 11. Nd2 Na6 12. h3 Bc8 13. Nc4 $18 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ge2e4]}) ({The same belongs to} 10... Bf5 $2 11. Nd2 $1 Na6 12. e4 ({even though} 12. Nc4 $5 {may be objectively the best, it is recommendable for practical reasons to exclude the jumps to the 4th rank and the required calculations}) 12... Bd7 13. Nc4 {[%csl Rd6]} b5 14. Nxd6 Bg4 15. f3 Qxd6 16. fxg4 c4 17. Bf4 Qb6+ 18. Be3 $16 {D. Nguyen - A. Gabrielian, Lichess.org INT, 2020}) (10... h6 {is a waiting move -} 11. a4 $5 ({an adequate reaction rather than} 11. e4 Bg4) ({or} 11. Bf4 g5 {with decent counterchances}) 11... Ne4 (11... Na6 12. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ge2e4]}) 12. Nxe4 Rxe4 13. Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd2c3]} ({A very clever attempt to make use of the new location of Black's h-pawn instead of the common} 13. Nd2 Rb4 $13) 13... Bxb2 14. Bxh6 $36) 11. Nxe4 Rxe4 12. Qc2 $1 {An essential subtlety in the fight for the central squares.} ({Or} 12. Nd2 Re8 {, but White can chase the rook while continuing the development.}) 12... Re8 ({The tactical justification of White's last move is revealed after} 12... Bf5 $6 13. Bh3 $1 Na6 ({agreeing to the wrecking of the kingside structure, but the rook will find itself in a very precarious situation after} 13... Re5 14. Bxf5 Rxf5 15. Kg2 $16 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge2e4]}) 14. Bxf5 gxf5 15. Ng5 Re5 (15... Nb4 16. Qb1) 16. Bf4 Nb4 17. Qb3 $18 {Xiong - Jones, Wijk aan Zee, 2017.}) 13. e4 Bg4 {Black's relatively best reply, as can be seen in the following lines:} (13... b5 14. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ga1d1]}) (13... Nd7 14. Bf4 Qe7 15. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Gc2d2,Gb2b4]}) (13... Na6 {is strongly met by} 14. Bg5 $1 Qb6 15. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4]} Qxb2 16. Qxb2 Bxb2 17. Rab1 ({worth checking is the attractive idea for} 17. Nc4 $5) 17... Bg7 18. Nc4 Bf8 19. e5 dxe5 20. d6 $36) 14. Bg5 $1 {White has no reason to refrain from the natural text move.} (14. Nd2 $143 Na6 15. a3 b5 $13 {Grischuk - Svidler, Moscow 2018.}) 14... Qc7 15. Nd2 Na6 (15... b5 $6 16. Bf1 (16. a4 $16) 16... Bd7 17. a4 bxa4 18. Bf4 $16 {and it is hard for Black to meet the imminent jump to the c4-square, Y. Parkhov - V. Mikhalevski, Ramat Gan, 2020.}) 16. Rac1 {This extra possibility is already a big achievement compared to the abovementioned game Grischuk - Svidler. White has more promising options, such as} (16. Bf1 $5 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4]}) ({and} 16. Qb3 $5) 16... h6 ({Here too,} 16... b5 {can be seriously questioned by} 17. a4) 17. Be3 Bd7 18. Bf1 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rc7]} *

