{[%evp 0,20,25,26,21,10,16,-9,17,17,17,17,28,28,68,30,30,30,36,43,42,42,42]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 Na6 {A typical route for this knight in many Benoni lines.} 11. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ge2e4] As Nb8 cannot oppose it any longer, the Nf3 pirouette is gaining in importance.} (11. e4 Bg4 $13) ({White's most popular move is} 11. Bf4 {, including in the recent practice.}) 11... Nc7 12. a4 $1 {The most logical and consistent continuation.} ({Instead,} 12. e4 b5 {can give rise to complications, for example} 13. e5 $5 dxe5 14. d6 Qxd6 15. Bxa8 Nxa8 16. Nde4 $1 ({Black seems to have ample compensation after} 16. Nxb5 Qb8 17. Nc3 Nc7 18. Nde4 Ne6 19. Be3 Rd8 20. Qb3 Qa8 21. f3 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 Nd4 23. Bxd4 Be6 24. Qa3 cxd4 $44) ({with two pawns for the exchange the situation seems optimistic for him after} 16. a4 b4 17. Nce4 Qc6 18. Qf3 Bf5 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Ne4 Qc6 21. g4 Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Qxe4 23. Rxe4 Nc7 24. Be3 Ne6 25. g5 Rd8 {as well}) 16... Nxe4 (16... Qc6 $6 17. Qd6) 17. Nxe4 Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Bg4 19. Re1 f5 20. Nxc5 Nb6 21. a4 bxa4 22. Nxa4 Nc4 $44 {/}) 12... b5 $146 {Nevertheless, Black is looking for queenside counterplay at any cost.} ({Besides, in reply to} 12... b6 {White can already execute} 13. e4 {with full comfort.}) ({Perhaps Black's only reasonable alternative is to direct the other knight to the center, e.g.} 12... Nd7 13. Nc4 $140 Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 {, when White can reasonably use its absence and demonstrate intentions on the kingside by the energetic} 15. h4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5]} Bd7 (15... Bg4 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bd2 $16) (15... Qe7 16. Bg5 Qf8 17. Qd2 $16) 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bd2 f5 18. Bg5 Bf6 19. Qd2 $16) (12... Rb8 13. Nc4 b6 {looks too slow in the view of} 14. Bf4 Bf8 15. e4 Ba6 16. b3 $16) 13. axb5 Bd7 14. Nc4 {In combination with the next move - a solid positional approach.} (14. Qb3 Rb8 {is yielding to Black sufficient counterplay in the spirit of the Volga gambit, for example} 15. Rxa7 Nxb5 16. Nxb5 Bxb5 17. Nc4 {and now the vigorous} Ng4 $1 (17... Bxc4 {is playable, but it is preferable to open the big diagonal in front of the other bishop beforehand, for instance} 18. Qxc4 Rb4 19. Qa6 Qb8 {and the b-pawn has still to be attacked by Bg7}) 18. Qc2 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Rb4 20. Qc2 Qb6 21. Ra2 Rb8 {, when White has hardly anything better than repeating the moves by} 22. Bf3 Ne5 23. Bg2 Ng4 $11) 14... Nxb5 15. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Gc4,Rd6][%cal Gd2c3,Ga1a7] Indeed, White has many possibilities, but this small consolidating touch seems to be the easiest way to fix the strategical achievements on the queenside.} *

