{[%evp 0,53,20,20,14,5,-1,-23,14,10,12,20,34,34,40,33,33,27,27,23,17,17,36,20,18,15,16,14,19,-24,-4,16,15,14,1,9,2,-11,11,-19,-8,-13,-16,-20,-20,-29,-32,-23,-26,-17,-38,-38,-44,-38,-34,-44]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Bf4 $1 {The most principled continuation.} ({It is worth remembering that} 11. e4 {is met by the usual for the Benoni counterstrike} b5 $1 $13) ({In case of the preparatory} 11. a4 {Black has a good reason to revert to the idea for} Ne4 12. Nxe4 $140 Rxe4 $13 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge4b4] It will be useful for the readers to compare the following positions to the 9th Chapter and advantages of Nb8-d7 to the modest a7-a6.}) 11... Ng4 {A characteristic situation for the Benoni - in many variations, Black's handling is based entirely on tactical means. Here the vulnerable d6-pawn is indirectly defended.} ({A tactical oversight is} 11... Qe7 $2 12. Nb5) ({Similar to the main text,} 11... Nh5 {is best countered by} 12. Bg5 Qc7 13. a4 a6 14. e4 $16) 12. Bg5 $5 (12. Qd2 {Donchenko - Vitiugov, Tornelo INT, 2021, allows} Nde5 $13) ({Black is fine after} 12. h3 Nge5 13. Ne4 Qe7 {as well.}) 12... f6 (12... Qb6 13. Qb3 a6 14. Qxb6 Nxb6 {took place in Kilgus - Rakhmangulova, Terme Catez, 2022, when} 15. Bf4 $5 {is a possible improvement, for example} Bxc3 (15... Nc4 16. Rac1 {[%cal Gb2b3]}) 16. bxc3 Nxd5 17. Bxd6 Nxc3 18. Bxc5 $14 {with lasting advantage due to the pair of bishops}) ({In reply to} 12... Qc7 {White has an intriguing concrete idea, namely} 13. Qa4 $5 $146 Ndf6 (13... Nge5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 (14... Rxe5 15. Bf4 $16) 15. Bf4 $16) (13... Ngf6 14. Qf4 $36 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 14. h3 h6 15. Bd2 $1 (15. Bf4 $143 Ne5) 15... Ne5 ({after} 15... Bd7 {White should stick to the idea for preserving the queen on the 4th rank -} 16. Qc4 {with probable transposition}) 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 ({the significance of White's move 15 is revealed after} 16... dxe5 $6 17. Qh4 g5 $140 18. Qc4 $16) 17. e4 Bd7 18. Qc4 {[%csl Rb5]} Ree8 19. a4 $14) 13. Bf4 $5 $146 {It makes sense to lure Nd7 to the center, either.} ({The practice has seen} 13. Bd2 a6 14. a4 Nge5 {Misericordia - Billio, LSS email, 2019}) 13... Nde5 ({The retreat} 13... Nge5 {is already a small concession, White can also successfully probe for weaknesses on the queenside by} 14. Rb1 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nf7 (14... g5 15. Bd2) 15. b4 b6 16. Qc2 $14) (13... g5 14. Bd2 {may just transpose.}) 14. h3 g5 (14... Nxf3+ $6 {will be instructively answered with} 15. exf3 Ne5 16. Bxe5 $1 fxe5 17. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc3e4] , reaching a position that is more typical for KID. Here the proud Bg7 lacks good prospects, and an eventual trade of the light-squared ones will emphasize this fact.}) 15. Bd2 Nxf3+ 16. exf3 Rxe1+ (16... Ne5 $6 17. Ne4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gf3f4,Gd2c3]}) 17. Qxe1 Ne5 18. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Rg5] a quiet retreat with double purpose - White avoids the created threat against his h-pawn and prevents, like, 17.Ne4 from above, the possible f6-f5.} ({Perhaps} 18. f4 {is a bit premature, e.g.} gxf4 19. Bxf4 (19. gxf4 Ng6) 19... f5 $13) 18... Nc4 ({After} 18... h6 $6 {White can resolutely go for} 19. f4 gxf4 (19... Nc4 20. Be1 f5 21. Bf1 Nb6 22. a4 $16) 20. Bxf4 $36 Nd3 $140 $6 21. Qd2 Nxf4 22. Qxf4 f5 23. Re1 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Rf5,Rg8,Rh6][%cal Gc3b5]}) ({In case of} 18... Bf5 {there are also little reasons to postpone} 19. f4 {and now:} gxf4 (19... Nd3 {is inviting an original pawn sacrifice -} 20. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2f5]} gxf4 21. Ne4 $1 Nb4 22. Qb3 fxg3 23. Qxg3 {with plenty of activity, an attractive sample line is going on with} Bxe4 24. Bxe4 Kh8 25. Kh1 Qf8 26. Rg1 f5 27. Bc3 Bd4 28. Bxf5 Nxd5 29. Bxd4+ cxd4 30. Qg2 Ne7 31. Bxh7 $1 Qh6 (31... Kxh7 $2 32. Qe4+ Nf5 33. Rg5 $1) 32. Be4 Rg8 33. Qf3 Rf8 34. Qg3 $16) 20. Bxf4 {has some similarity with the 18....h6?! line from above, Black can opt for the more solid} Qe7 21. Qe3 Re8 {, though White's chances are higher after} 22. Re1 $14) 19. a4 $1 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 f5 {Black has not only succeeded with this push but has also eliminated the counterpart of Bg7. However, exchanging with the other bishop will make him take care of the light squares on the kingside, so} 21. Bf1 h6 ({It is difficult to imagine a better way for justifying White's last move than} 21... Bd7 $6 22. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rg5] and White is going to enjoy the e6-outpost after} h6 23. Re1 $16 {[%csl Re6]}) ({Indeed, the preliminary} 21... a6 {is preferable, albeit insufficient for equality because of} 22. a5 Bd7 23. Na4 $16 {and, especially if opposite-colored bishops remain on the board, Black will have problems in defending the kingside and the f5-pawn in particular.}) 22. Bd3 Bd7 23. Qc2 Qc8 (23... Qf6 $143 24. Bb5 $1) 24. Bb5 {By this logical follow-up from a strategic point of view, White is also avoiding a trap.} (24. Nb5 $5 c4 $1 {is a promise for rich counterplay, for instance} 25. Bxc4 ({of course not} 25. Nxd6 $4 cxd3 $19) 25... Qc5 26. Rc1 Rc8 27. Qb1 Qb4 28. Bf1 $44 {/}) 24... a6 25. Bxd7 Qxd7 26. Re1 {[%csl Re6]} Be5 27. a5 $14 *

