{[%evp 0,37,20,15,15,-6,4,-14,10,12,7,7,25,36,40,33,33,27,23,19,19,39,72,23,62,70,70,55,38,59,59,53,57,47,79,71,77,48,86,92]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 a6 11. a4 b6 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7e7]} (11... Bf5 $2 12. Nd2 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd2c4]}) (11... Bg4 $2 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) ({In reply to} 11... Qc7 {useful is} 12. h3 $1 ({contrary to the leading text, now} 12. e4 {is not very precise, Black seems in full order after} Bg4 13. Qc2 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nbd7 $13 {, see also the note for 13.h3 below}) (12. Bf4 Nbd7 {reaches the deviation with 12...Qc7 in the last Chapter}) 12... Nbd7 (12... Ne4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Qc2 Rb4 15. Ra2 {[%cal Gc1d2]} a5 (15... b5 16. axb5 Rxb5 17. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c3]}) 16. Bd2 Na6 17. Bc3 Bd7 18. e4 $16) 13. e4 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Rb8 14. Bf1 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4]}) 12. e4 {The most radical measure in the fight for the center.} ({Black's Nb8 is lacking the a6-square and the manoeuvre} 12. Nd2 {, which may help Black to trade it after} Nbd7 13. Nc4 $140 Ne5 $13 {is not pretending for much}) ({Besides the textmove, worth trying is} 12. Bf4 $5 {[%csl Rd6]} Ne4 13. Ra3 ({the insertion of the moves with the a-pawns enables this opportunity in addition to the more common} 13. Qc1) 13... Ra7 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Nd2 Rb4 16. b3 {, when 17.Nc4 has to be neutralized.}) (12. h3 $5 {is directed against the possible pin. In his turn, Black can grab the ultimate opportunity for exploiting the e4-square by} Ne4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Qc2 Rb4 15. Ra2 {[%cal Gc1d2]} Nd7 {, intending the unusual exchange sacrifice} 16. Bd2 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 17. Bxb4 axb4 $44 {under better circumstances than in the branch with 11...Qc7.}) 12... Bg4 {Black has waited enough with this sally, but, as we will see, the small step of his b7-pawn has drawbacks.} (12... Nbd7 $6 {is a worse version of the abovementioned line with 11...Qc7, here White can immediately point at the undefended d6-pawn with} 13. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) ({The rook lift} 12... Ra7 $6 13. Bf4 Rae7 {looks very attractive, but White can safely carry out his main strategical idea} 14. Nd2 Ng4 15. Nc4 Bd4 $140 16. Rf1 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 (18. Bg5 f6 19. Be3 $16 {, as in G. Kaidanov - R. Vazquez, Andorra, 1991, is a logical alternative, though White has a good reason to eliminate the defender of the dark squares and the d6-pawn in particular}) 18... Rxe5 19. f4 R5e7 20. Qd2 $16 {, forcing the opponent to reckon constantly with the central break, while the sound alternative plan with b2-b4 is also in the air.}) 13. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6] The best practical chance to confuse the opponent.} ({Instead, an automatical move like} 13. h3 {will provide the latter with enough time to regroup his army -} Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nbd7 15. Qe2 Qc7 $13) 13... Nh5 ({The problem with the undeveloped Nb8 is telling even stronger after} 13... Ra7 $6 14. Qd2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Rae7 16. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Rd6]}) 14. Be3 $146 ({In my opinion, White can prefer to increase the control over the d4-square by the text move to} 14. Bd2 {from Bai - Indjic, Pune, 2014.}) 14... Nd7 (14... Qc8 15. Qc2 {may transpose later.}) 15. Qc2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c4 {Otherwise, this pawn may have no other chance.} ({In case of} 16... Nhf6 17. Be2 $1 Qc8 (17... c4 18. Bxc4 Ng4 19. Bf4 Bd4 20. Rf1 Nc5 21. Kg2 $16) 18. b3 Ne5 19. Kg2 c4 {Black has finally succeeded with this push but at the cost of exposing the b6-pawn. However, before demonstrating his trumps on the queenside, White's best is to complete his mobilization by means of consolidating} 20. Rac1 $16) 17. Be2 $1 ({Less consistent is} 17. Bxh5 gxh5 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 18. Qe2 Ne5 19. Bd4 Nd3 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 {with plenty of counterplay for the pawn after} 21. Qxh5 Qf6 22. Re2 Re5 23. Qh3 Rg5 $44) 17... Rc8 18. Kg2 Nhf6 19. f3 $16 {[%csl Ge2,Ge3] White can gradually improve his position behind the shield of the solid center.} *

