{[%evp 0,39,20,15,18,4,4,-13,10,12,7,24,36,36,48,32,27,23,19,19,19,28,57,14,4,0,0,26,69,69,76,62,54,34,12,34,63,46,61,49,101,41]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 a6 11. a4 Ne4 {This active possibility has already been examined with the a-pawns still on their initial squares.} 12. Nxe4 (12. Ra3 Nd7 $13) 12... Rxe4 13. Qc2 $1 {The typical reaction, although here the rook has access to the b4-square.} ({Black seems in fine shape after} 13. Nd2 Rb4 14. Ra2 Nd7 15. b3 b5 16. axb5 (16. Ba3 a5 $1) 16... Rxb5 17. Bb2 Bxb2 18. Rxb2 a5 19. Ra2 Rb4 20. Qa1 Ne5 $11) 13... Rb4 ({As we already know,} 13... Bf5 $6 {fails to} 14. Bh3 $1 Nd7 $140 15. Bxf5 gxf5 16. Ng5 $16) ({Here} 13... Re8 {is by far not as necessary as in the relevant Chapter. As now the b7-b5 advance is disabled, White can go at once for the annoying} 14. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} ({the same move is critical after the familiar} 14. e4 Nd7 {, while the practice has seen instead the less effective} 15. Bg5 Qb6 16. Rab1 Ne5 $13 {Sevian - Caruana, Chess.com INT, 2019}) ({from the other side, the immediate} 14. Bg5 $5 {is worth checking}) 14... Bg4 (14... Qc7 15. Nd2 {leads to indisputable White's strategical advantage -} Nd7 16. Nc4 Ne5 17. Bxe5 $1 (17. Nxe5 Bxe5 $14) 17... Bxe5 18. a5 {[%csl Gc4]} Bd7 19. Nb6 Rad8 20. e3 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gb2b4]}) 15. a5 $1 (15. Nd2 $6 g5 16. Be3 {Nakamura - Sindarov, Warsaw, 2021,} Nd7 $132) 15... b5 ({in reply to} 15... Bxf3 {the capture} 16. exf3 $1 {is once again the most principled option, mostly because of the vulnerable d6-pawn}) (15... Nd7 {can be used immediately, after} 16. Bxd6 {Black may try to fish in muddy waters by 16....b5!? or play the restrained} Nf6 ({Black is facing a long-term defensive task in a bad ending after} 16... Qf6 17. Bf4 Qxb2 18. Qxb2 Bxb2 19. Rab1 Bc3 20. Bd2 Bxd2 21. Nxd2 Rxe2 22. Rxe2 Bxe2 23. Rxb7 $16) 17. Bf4 Bf5 {and now the precise} 18. Qc4 $1 Qxd5 $140 19. Ne5 Be4 20. Rad1 {provokes favorable exchanges and a pleasant edge for White -} Qxc4 21. Nxc4 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 $14 {/}) 16. axb6 Nd7 (16... Qxb6 $2 17. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 17. Bxd6 ({the resulting position after the text move may occur via the abovementioned 16....b5!?, while now White has the plausible alternative} 17. b7 $5 Ra7 18. Bxd6 Rxb7 19. Rxa6 Rxb2 20. Qa4 $16) 17... Qxb6 18. Bf4 Qxb2 19. Qxb2 Bxb2 20. Ra2 Bg7 21. e3 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rc5,Gd5]}) 14. Ra2 ({Another possibility is} 14. e4) 14... b5 (14... Nd7 15. Bd2 a5 16. Bc3 $14 {is very likely to transpose to move 17 in the leading text.}) ({Alternatively, the different route} 14... a5 15. Bd2 Na6 {does not bring any dividends to Black, as witnessed by} 16. Bc3 b5 (16... Bd7 17. e4 $16) 17. axb5 Rxb5 18. Qd2 Nb4 {in Rodshtein - Deac, Heraklion, 2017, when} 19. Ra3 $16 {is the simplest way to proceed.}) 15. axb5 Rxb5 16. Bd2 Nd7 (16... Bg4 17. Ng5 $1 h6 $2 {took place in Vrolijk - Bharath, Kavala, 2022, in which the first player passed through the small but powerful tactical operation} 18. Ne6 $1 fxe6 19. Qc4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gc4g4,Gd5e6] Instead, the game saw the second move of this beautiful short line.}) 17. Bc3 a5 18. Nd2 Nb6 19. e4 a4 20. h3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]} *

