{[%evp 0,39,30,30,27,-4,-3,-21,24,31,31,8,23,41,53,28,28,44,38,42,43,22,72,21,55,28,4,9,8,0,0,-17,5,-9,-7,-7,-29,-14,-6,-6,9,1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. Bf4 {A big tabiya for the whole fianchetto system against the Benoni. We have already examined a version of it with the a-pawns at their initial places, while that insertion adds new opportunities for both sides.} ({Besides, another critical variation is starting with} 12. e4 Ng4 $1 (12... Qc7 13. h3) 13. Nd2 Nge5 ({very bizarre is} 13... Nde5 $6 14. h3 Nh6 15. Bf1 f5 16. f4 Nef7 17. a5 $16 {and both Black's knights are awkwardly placed}) 14. Re3 $5 (14. Bf1 g5 {initiates a lively fight around the f4-square after the principled thrust} 15. f4 (15. Ra3 Qf6) 15... Ng6 16. Nf3 (16. f5 Nge5 $13) 16... gxf4 $1 ({instead, in the known practical example Black has unexpectedly sidestepped from the general idea by} 16... g4 $6 17. Nd2 Bd4+ 18. Kg2 Nf6 {So far Ding Liren - Navara, Prague, 2019, when} 19. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gc3e2] is strong enough}) 17. gxf4 Bh6 $1 18. f5 Bxc1 19. Qxc1 Nge5 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. Qh6 Kh8 $132 {[%csl Ge5]}) 14... g5 $1 {seems once again to be Black's best bet, for example} (14... c4 $5 {This usual for the Benoni push is, as a rule, the key to counterplay. Here, as well as in various of the following lines, it contains a pawn sacrifice in return for eliminating Bc1 and counterplay along the opened c-file, for example} 15. f4 Nd3 (15... Qb6 $2 16. Qe2) 16. Nxc4 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 {and now:} Qc7 {is definitely the critical continuation:} (17... Nb6 $6 {fails to impress for two reasons -} 18. Nd2 $5 ({or the consolidating} 18. Na3 Bd7 $140 19. b3) 18... Bd4 {, when} 19. Nf1 {is a very promising exchange sacrifice in the spirit of a popular Gruenfeld line -} Bxe3+ 20. Nxe3 $14 {[%cal Gd1d4]}) 18. Na3 $5 (18. b3 b5 $1 (18... Qc5 19. e5 {[%cal Gc3e4]} b5 20. Ne4 Qa7 21. Nexd6 bxc4 22. Nxc4 $44) 19. axb5 Rb8 $13) 18... Qb6 (18... Qc5 19. Qd2) 19. Qd2 Qb4 $1 {takes the key c4-square under control and Na3 is therefore limited to} ({as before, Black does not benefit at all from} 19... Bd4 $2 20. Nc4 Bxe3+ 21. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 22. Nxe3 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge3c4]}) (19... Nc5 {allows} 20. Nc4 Qb4 21. Ne2 $1 (21. Nxd6 $2 Nb3) 21... Qxd2 22. Nxd2 Nxa4 (22... Bxb2 23. Rc2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 23. Nc4 Bf8 24. b3 Nc5 25. Nb6 Rb8 26. h3 $14) 20. Nc2 $1 (20. Kh1 Nc5 $44) 20... Qxb2 {Now White can put his hopes on the breakthrough} 21. e5 $1 (21. Rb1 Bxc3 22. Qd1 Qa2 23. Rxc3 Qxa4 $13 {also deserves to be thoroughly checked}) 21... Qb6 22. e6 Nc5 23. Rce1 Kh8 24. exf7 Rf8 25. Kh1 {The second wave is about to come, but Black has an instructive antidote against the Nc2 penetration either -} Bd7 26. Nd4 Nxa4 (26... Rxf7 $143 27. Ne6 $36) 27. Ne6 Bxc3 $1 28. Rxc3 Qb4 29. Nxf8 Rxf8 30. Rc2 Qxd2 31. Rxd2 Rxf7 $44 32. Re6 $140 $5 Bxe6 33. dxe6 Re7 34. Rxd6 Nc5 35. Bd5 Kg7 $11) (14... Nb6 {is again less to the point because of} 15. Qf1 $1 a5 (15... Ng4 16. Re2) 16. h3 $6 (16. Nb5 $1 $16) 16... c4 $1 17. Kh2 Bd7 $132 18. f4 Nd3 19. Nxc4 Nxc1 20. Rxc1 Nxc4 21. Qxc4 Qb6 22. Qe2 Rac8 $44 {in another game Ding Liren - Navara, Prague, 2019}) 15. f4 Ng6 16. Nc4 Nb6 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. f5 (18. a5 Qd8) 18... Ne5 19. Qh5 Qd8 (19... h6 $6 20. h4 $40) (19... c4 $5 {is once again an essential resource at Black's disposal -} 20. a5 (20. Qxg5 h6 21. Qh5 Nd3 22. Nd1 Nxc1 23. Rxc1 Bd7 24. Kh1 Bxa4 25. Re2 Qd8 26. Ne3 Qg5 27. Qf3 Be5 $13) 20... Qd4 21. Ne2 Qd1+ 22. Bf1 h6 23. h4 Nd3 24. hxg5 Nxc1 25. Rxc1 Qd2 26. Rf3 Qxg5 (26... Rxe4 $6 {is ill-timed, for} 27. g6 $1 {does not leave Black time to capture Ne2 and he has to reconcile himself with} fxg6 28. Qxg6 Qg5 29. Qxg5 hxg5 30. Nc3 $1 Re5 31. g4 $14) 27. Qxg5 hxg5 28. Rxc4 Bxb2 29. Rb3 Bf6 30. Nc3 Rb8 $13) (19... Bf6 {is likely to transpose to the next line, as the g5-pawn needs protection}) 20. Nd1 (20. h4 g4) 20... Bf6 21. Nf2 Kh8 $13 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gg8g7]}) (12. h3 {prevents Ng4, but the jump in the other direction} Ne4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 $13 {reaches a playable position from the previous Chapter, in which the insertion of h2-h3 and a7-a6 does not worsen Black's prospects at least.}) 12... Ng4 {This knight jump is once again the most popular continuation.} ({As we already know from the 7th Chapter, without the movements of the a-pawns} 12... Qe7 {is a tactical mistake. It has the right to exist; White's best is the prophylaxis} 13. h3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} ({thus the familiar} 13. e4 Ng4 {is avoided}) 13... Nh5 (13... Rb8 $143 14. e4) 14. Bg5 Qf8 15. e4 Rb8 16. g4 h6 (16... Nhf6 17. Bf4 {is almost the same}) 17. Bd2 Nhf6 18. Bf4 {and now:} Nh7 (18... h5 19. g5 (19. e5 $5 {is possible, but White is not in a hurry}) 19... Nh7 20. Qd2 $16) 19. Qc2 Qe7 20. Bg3 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5] Carolei - McKenzie, ICCF email, 2013. In both cases, White has secured the powerful position of his bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal.}) (12... Nh5 13. Bg5 Qc7 (13... Qb6 14. Qc2) 14. e4 {is already a considerable achievement for White, for example} Rb8 (14... h6 15. Be3 $16) (14... Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qd2 Bd7 17. h3 $16 {Dmitriev - Doric, ICCF email, 2017}) 15. g4 $5 Nhf6 (15... h6 $6 16. gxh5 hxg5 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Nxg5 Ne5 19. f4 $18) 16. e5 $5 ({A brave and reasonable attempt to cut the knot. Instead, White can be patient and prefer} 16. h3 {and the solid strategical plan from above}) 16... dxe5 (16... Nxg4 17. e6 Ndf6 18. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf3g5,Gf4d6]} h6 19. Qd2 g5 20. Bg3 Nh5 {White is much better mobilized and, to increase the initiative, he should not hesitate about sacrificing a piece -} 21. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 22. Qxg5 Nhf6 (22... Nxg3 $2 23. Qxg4 $18) ({after} 22... Ngf6 23. Ne4 Nxe4 24. Bxe4 {Black should transpose by retreating the knight rather than} Nxg3 $2 {, which is refuted by} 25. exf7+ Qxf7 26. Bg6 $1 Rxe1+ $140 27. Rxe1 Qf8 28. Qh4 Bh6 29. hxg3 $18) 23. Ne4 Nxe4 24. Bxe4 Nf6 25. Bf5 b5 26. Re3 $40) 17. d6 {with domination -} Qb6 (17... Qd8 18. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gd5e7,Gd5c7] Tan Zangyi - Abrahamyan, Astana, 2019}) 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. g5 Nd7 20. Nd5 Qd8 21. h4 Kh8 22. Ra3 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Gd5,Gd6,Rd7]}) ({My suggestion is to meet} 12... Qc7 {also with the prophylactic} 13. h3 $5 ({As mentioned, the main theoretical discussion emerges after the sequence} 13. e4 Ng4 14. Nd2 Nge5 15. Bf1) 13... Ne4 (13... Rb8 $6 14. e4 {is usually a considerable achievement for White and this case is not an exception, for example} Nh5 (14... b5 $2 15. axb5 axb5 16. Bf1 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc3b5]}) 15. Bd2 (15. Bg5 $5) 15... b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bf1 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} c4 {is trying to defend the b5-pawn, but here comes again the well-timed} (17... b4 18. Nb5 Qb6 19. g4 $1 Bxb2 (19... Nhf6 20. Bf4 $1 Nxe4 $140 21. Nd2 $18) 20. Ra2 (20. gxh5 $5 Bxa1 21. Qxa1 $16) 20... Nhf6 21. Rxb2 Ba6 22. Nc7 $1 Qxc7 23. Bxa6 Nxe4 24. Rb3 $16 {E. Campbell - L. Wedel, ICCF email, 2018}) 18. g4 $1 (18. b4 {is the right, but slightly premature idea -} cxb3 19. Nxb5 Qb6 20. Rb1 Nc5 $13 {Maiorov - Narayanan, Runavik, 2017}) 18... Nhf6 (18... b4 19. gxh5 bxc3 20. Bxc3 $16) 19. b4 $1 (19. Nd4 b4 20. Ncb5 Qb6 $13) 19... cxb3 20. Nxb5 $1 ({a logical improvement upon} 20. Qxb3 $6 {from Vantika - Shyam, Abu Dhabi, 2019, which could continue with} b4 $1 21. Nb5 Qd8 22. Bxb4 Nxe4 $13) 20... Rxb5 (20... Qd8 21. Nxd6 $18) ({White's precise move 18 has closed the big diagonal in front of Bg7, therefore in the new situation} 20... Qb6 {is strongly met by} 21. Ba5 $1 {and the intermediate b3-b2 is lacking venom}) 21. Bxb5 b2 (21... Nxe4 22. Rc1) 22. Rb1 Nxe4 23. Ng5 $1 f5 24. Ne6 Rxe6 25. dxe6 Ndc5 26. Qc2 Bxe6 27. Rxb2 $18) (13... Nh5 14. Bd2 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 {can be seriously tested by} 15. b3 $5 $146 (15. Nd2 Rb4 $132) (15. Qc2 Rb4 16. Ra2 b5 17. axb5 Rxb5 $13 {Vantika - Gaponenko, Abu Dhabi, 2019}) 15... b5 {makes sense - Black plays a program move without committing himself at once.} ({Black can immediately accept the exchange -} 15... Bxa1 16. Qxa1 {and now:} Rb4 (16... Rxf4 17. gxf4 Qd8 18. e4 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) (16... Re8 17. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gd2c4]}) (16... b5 $6 17. Nh2 $1 {[%cal Gh2g4]} Re8 (17... Rxf4 18. gxf4 c4 19. Ng4 $16) 18. Ng4 $16) 17. Nd2 Ne5 18. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5f6]} b5 19. axb5 Bb7 20. bxa6 Rxa6 21. Qc3 Qa5 (21... Rd4 22. Ne4 $16 {Here is an illustrative line about the difficulties in front of Black -} Qa5 $6 23. Nf6+ Kg7 {(otherwise, after the trade of the queens, f2-f4 is going to trap the knight in the middle of the board!)} 24. Qc1 Bc8 25. Bh6+ Kh8 26. Be3 Kg7 (26... Rb4 $2 27. Bxc5 $1) 27. Ne8+ Kf8 28. Bxd4 cxd4 29. Nxd6 Rxd6 $140 30. Qxc8+ Kg7 31. Rd1 Rd8 32. Qc1 Qa2 33. Qf4 Qxe2 34. Qxd4 {and White should win}) 22. Nc4 $1 (22. Ne4 Rxb3 $1 {is a nasty trick that must be avoided}) 22... Rxc4 (22... Nxc4 $2 {is very nicely refuted by} 23. Qf6 $1 $18 {[%cal Gg5h6]}) 23. Qxa5 Rxa5 24. bxc4 Nxc4 25. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gg5f6]}) (15... Nf6 $5 16. Rc1 $1 {[%cal Gb3b4]} Re8 (16... b5 $6 17. Nd4 $1) (16... Nh5 17. Bd2 Bd7 18. Nh2 Re7 19. e4 Rae8 20. b4 $16) 17. b4 $1 c4 (17... b6 $6 18. a5 $16) 18. e4 $1 ({in such structure} 18. Nd2 {fails to impress, after} b5 19. e4 Nd7 $13 {that knight is needed on the d4-square}) 18... Rxe4 (18... Nxe4 $2 19. Nd2 $18) 19. Rxe4 Nxe4 20. Qe2 Nf6 21. Rxc4 Qd8 22. Nd4 $14 {[%cal Gd4c6]}) (15... Re8 16. Rc1 b5 $6 (16... Nf6 {is back to the abovementioned 15...Nf6}) 17. e4) (15... Rb4 {looks aimless, as the rook does not have any targets in sight and it will be chased back, for instance} 16. Rc1 b5 17. Bd2 Re4 18. Qc2 Re8 19. Bc3 $14 (19. e4 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3]})) (15... Rb8 16. Nd2 Rb4 (16... Rxf4 $6 17. gxf4 Bxa1 18. Qxa1 b5 19. e4 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 17. Nc4 $1 (17. Ne4 Ne5 {and Black's potential should not be underestimated, for example} 18. Bd2 Rxe4 $1 19. Bxe4 Bxh3 $44 {with very active piece play}) 17... Ne5 18. Na3 $1 ({A remarkable idea rather than the dry} 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Nxe5 dxe5 $11 {[%cal Gb4d4]}) 18... c4 {Yet another stunning calm move, which continues the hunt.} ({the rook is in danger of being trapped after both} 18... Rd4 19. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Ga3c2]}) ({and} 18... Bf5 19. Bd2) 19. Rc1 $1 b5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Bd2 Qc5 ({it is this resource, which helps Black to stay in the game;} 21... Rxb3 $2 22. Qxb3 $1 $18 {is curtains}) 22. bxc4 ({Rb4 is untouchable for a while, but White will consent with a healthy pawn up as well. Of course, if he wishes so, there is also a repetition by} 22. Be3 Qc7 23. Bd2 $11) 22... Ra4 (22... bxc4 23. Bxb4 Rxb4 24. Rb1 Bf5 25. Nc2 Rxb1 26. Qxb1 $16) (22... Nxc4 23. Bxb4 Qxb4 24. Nxc4 bxc4 25. Qc2 $16) 23. Nxb5 Rxc4 24. Nc3 $16) 16. Nd2 (16. axb5 Bxa1 17. Qxa1 Bb7 18. Bh6 f6 $13) 16... Rb4 (16... Rxf4 17. gxf4 Bxa1 18. Qxa1 Bb7 19. e4 Re8 20. Re3 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge4e5]}) 17. axb5 Bb7 ({here} 17... Bxa1 18. Qxa1 Bb7 {is running into the deflecting blow} 19. b6 $1 Nxb6 $140 20. Ne4 Rxe4 21. Bxe4 $16) 18. Ne4 Qb6 ({the same original intermezzo is working fine after} 18... Bxa1 19. b6 $1 {, facing Black with a hard choice of either transpose to the line from above or enter} Rxb6 20. Qxa1 $36) 19. Qc2 $1 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 axb5 21. Rxa8+ Bxa8 22. Bh6 {White has rich compensation for the exchange. Even more, that rook is quite limited, e.g.} Rd4 23. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} Rb4 {Black would be happy to end the game by repetition, but there is} 24. Qb2 f6 25. Be3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc3a2]} Rd4 (25... Ne5 26. Na2) 26. Bxd4 cxd4 27. Nb1 Ne5 28. b4 Bb7 29. Nd2 d3 30. Nb3 dxe2 31. Qxe2 $14 {[%csl Rb5,Rd6,Rf6,Rg8][%cal Gg1g2,Gf2f4,Gb3a5]}) 13. h3 Nge5 14. Ne4 Qe7 {The other options are hardly recommendable:} (14... Nxf3+ $6 15. exf3 {[%csl Rd6]} Ne5 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bd2 Bf5 (17... f5 $2 18. Bg5) 18. a5 Nd3 19. Re2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c3]}) (14... Nf6 $6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 (16... dxe5 17. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd2c4,Ga4a5]}) 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. e4 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1d2]}) (14... Qc7 $6 15. Rc1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (15. b4 $5) 15... b6 16. b4 $16) 15. Qc1 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Rh7h6,Gf4h6]} (15. a5 $5 {, aiming at a grip on the queenside, is the major alternative:} h6 (15... b5 16. axb6 Rb8 (16... Nxb6 $2 17. Bg5 $16 f6 $2 18. Nxe5 fxg5 19. Nc6 $18) 17. Nxe5 ({the move order in eliminating the defenders of the c4-height really matters, as shown by} 17. Bg5 Qf8) 17... Nxe5 18. Bg5 $1 f6 19. Bd2 Rxb6 20. Bc3 f5 21. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2]}) 16. Ned2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] is the most precise way to the desired strategical purpose, for instance} (16. h4 b5 17. axb6 Rb8 18. Qc1 f5 19. Ned2 Rxb6 20. Bxe5 Nxe5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Nc4 Rb4 23. Nxe5 {It is probably not to White's liking to part with the knight, but the moves by the h-pawns, besides depriving him of the g5-square, have provided the opponent with other possibilities, such as meeting e2-e4 with the fascinating exchange sacrifice 23...Rxc4!? 24.Qxc4 f4} Qxe5 24. Qxh6 Kf7 25. h5 ({or} 25. Bf3 Qg7 {- Black does not mind the trade of the queens, as the queenside activity should compensate the missing pawn}) 25... Qg7 26. Qg5 Qf6 27. hxg6+ Qxg6 28. Qxg6+ Kxg6 29. Ra2 Bb7 $44) (16. g4 b6 17. axb6 Rb8 $13) 16... g5 17. Bxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Nc4 Bd7 $140 20. Qc2 Rac8 21. e3 Bb5 22. Bf1 $14) ({When Bf4 is not harassed, then the common maneuver for eliciting f7-f6} 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bf4 {is by no means obliged and advantageous, given the two sacrificed tempi. Indeed, after} Nf7 17. Ned2 g5 18. Be3 f5 19. Nc4 b6 $13 {White is far from using the weakened e6-square.}) (15. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nf6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bxe5 (17. a5 Bd7 $11) 17... Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. e4 Bd7 20. a5 Rab8 21. b4 c4 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6]}) (15. Qc2 h6 16. a5 Rb8 $13) 15... b6 ({Black can opt for a more active plan with} 15... Rb8 16. h4 b5 (16... b6 {does not correlate well with the previous move and, similar to the leading text, White can rely on} 17. Ra3 Qf8 $140 18. h5 $36) (16... f5 17. Neg5 Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Ne5 19. Bg2 $14) 17. axb5 {and now:} Rxb5 (17... axb5 $6 18. Ra7 Rb7 19. Ra6 Rb6 20. Nxe5 $1 Bxe5 (20... Bxa6 $2 21. Nc6 $18) 21. Ra7 Rb7 22. Bxe5 Nxe5 23. Rxb7 Bxb7 24. Qg5 $1 Qxg5 25. hxg5 Rd8 26. f4 Nc4 (26... Ng4 $2 27. Nf6+ Nxf6 28. gxf6 $18 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ge4e5]}) 27. b3 Na5 28. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gg1f2]}) 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 (18... Nxe5 19. Bg5 f6 20. Bd2 $14) 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 (19... Nxe5 20. Qg5 $1 Qxg5 21. hxg5 Rd8 22. f4 Ng4 (22... Nc4 23. Kf2) 23. Bf3 $16) 20. Ra3 f5 21. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ge2e4]}) (15... f5 {is very similar to the aforementioned subline with 16....f5 and may easily transpose to it after} 16. Neg5 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Ne5 18. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Re6]}) 16. Ra3 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga3e3]} ({A recent game has seen the trendy advance} 16. h4 Bb7 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 $132 {Dardha - Indjic, Germany, 2022, but the useful innovation in the text keeps all the options open.}) 16... Bb7 ({Or} 16... Qf8 17. g4 $1 {Here is the alternative approach - apart from expanding on the kingside, White can make good use of the g3-square for many pieces of his.} f6 ({Black should play a move like} 17... f5 $6 {with care, as shown by} 18. Neg5 Nxf3+ 19. Rxf3 Ne5 20. Rg3 fxg4 21. Ne6 $16) 18. Bd2 $5 (18. Bg3 $14) 18... Nf7 (18... Nxg4 $6 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. hxg4 Ne5 21. g5 {is about to prove the hypothesis about how unfavorable the exchange of a central pawn for a flank one is. Yet another small exchange operation is confirming it after} Nxf3+ 22. Rxf3 f5 23. Bf4 Be5 24. Re3 $1 Bxf4 25. Rxe8+ Kf7 26. Rd8 $1 Bh2+ 27. Kh1 Qxd8 28. Kxh2 Qd6+ 29. f4 Bd7 30. Kg3 Re8 31. b3 $16) 19. Ng3 Bb7 20. Nh2 b5 21. a5 c4 22. f4 Nc5 23. Qc2 $14) 17. Nxe5 ({Once again} 17. Bg5 {does not seem fully justified, for example} Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 (18. exf3 Qf8 $13) 18... Qf8 19. Bf4 Ne5 20. Rb3 ({Such shift of attention to the queenside is more or less obligatory, as after} 20. Bg2 b5 {Black can himself seize the initiative on this half of the board}) 20... Bxd5 21. Rxb6 Reb8 22. a5 {with the balanced game, as the following exemplary lines prove -} Rxb6 23. axb6 Rb8 24. Bxe5 (24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25. Qd2 Qxb6 26. Bxd5 Qxb2 27. Qxb2 Rxb2 28. Ra1 Rxe2 29. Rxa6 {and White has enough compensation for the pawn, but not more}) 24... Bxe5 25. Nxc5 dxc5 26. Bxd5 Rxb6 27. b3 Qd6 $1 28. Rd1 (28. Qc4 Bxg3 {with guaranteed perpetual if White accepts the piece}) 28... Bd4 $11) 17... Nxe5 18. g4 $1 {Here comes the new White's resource again!} (18. Bg5 $5 f6 19. Bd2 f5 20. Ng5 b5 21. Ne6 b4 22. Bg5 (22. Rb3 a5) 22... Qd7 23. Re3 Rac8 $13) 18... b5 (18... Bxd5 $6 19. Nxd6 $1 Qxd6 20. Rd1 Qe7 21. Bxd5 Rad8 22. Re3 $16) 19. g5 $1 {[%csl Rf6]} b4 20. Re3 $36 {[%cal Ge3e8,Gf4g3,Gf2f4]} *

